<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Count Up Timer Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Starts a visible timer that counts upward from zero when triggered. Can be used for timed mission logic, challenges, and cone penalty setups.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Count Up Timer Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Count Up Timer</Bold> Event Point starts a visible timer that counts upward from
        zero when the Event Point is triggered.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is useful when the mission needs to show the player how long they have been doing
        something, how long they have taken to complete a challenge, or how much time has accumulated
        during a timed sequence.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Count Up Timer can be used with <Bold>Cone Penalties</Bold>, but it is not limited to cone
        challenges. It is a general visible count-up timer that can be placed behind any mission
        trigger where a visible increasing timer is useful.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_count_up_timer_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Simple summary:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Count Up Timer starts a visible timer at 0 and counts upward while active.
                    It has no type-specific properties; the important setup is when and how it is triggered.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding a Count Up Timer Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add one, click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select
        <Bold>Count Up Timer</Bold> from the Event Point type list, and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window opens with the standard common properties and trigger
        settings. Count Up Timer does not have any additional type-specific fields.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_count_up_timer_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Count Up Timer uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point
        type, letter group, colour, position, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. The position is usually less important
        than it is for physical world objects, because the purpose of the Event Point is to start a
        visible timer rather than place a visible pickup or actor. However, it is still helpful to
        place it near the area or mission logic it belongs to so the file remains readable.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_count_up_timer_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Type-Specific Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Count Up Timer has <Bold>no type-specific properties</Bold>. There is no timer value to enter
        here and no item type, NPC type, object type, or special configuration section.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The key setup is the <Bold>trigger</Bold>. The Event Point starts counting upward when its
        trigger condition is satisfied.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    If the timer does not start, look at the trigger configuration first.
                    Count Up Timer has no special internal settings; it depends on the trigger firing.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Count Up Timer should be placed behind the mission event that starts the timed section.
        This could be a player entering an area, pressing a switch, starting a race, accepting an
        objective, finishing a conversation, or any other mission condition.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Common trigger examples include:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Enters Radius</Bold> — the timer starts when the player enters an area.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Enters Cuboid</Bold> — the timer starts when the player enters a boxed region.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Uses in Radius</Bold> — the timer starts when the player uses a switch/object.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> — the timer starts after another Event Point has fired.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Conversation Finished</Bold> — the timer starts after dialogue completes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>None / Game Starts</Bold> — the timer starts immediately when the mission begins.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_count_up_timer_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical trigger detail:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Count Up Timer starts when its own trigger fires.
                    If you want a timed challenge to begin when the player enters an area, the Count Up Timer must use that area trigger or depend on another Event Point that uses that trigger.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Using Count Up Timer for Timed Mission Logic
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Count Up Timer can be used as part of a time-limit style mission setup. For example, the
        player enters an area and has a certain amount of time to complete a task. The timer counts
        up from zero, while other mission logic can decide what happens if the player takes too long
        or completes the task successfully.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A typical timed mission sequence might look like this:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>The player enters a trigger radius or starts the objective.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>The <Bold>Count Up Timer</Bold> starts and becomes visible.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>The player attempts to complete the objective before the time becomes too high.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Separate mission logic checks whether the task has been completed or failed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the player completes the task, the mission continues or awards the objective.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the player fails, another Event Point can trigger a mission failure or penalty.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Count Up Timer by itself only starts the visible count-up display. It does not automatically
        decide success or failure unless other Event Points are also used to check or respond to the
        timer/mission state.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Design note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Use Count Up Timer to show elapsed time. Use other Event Points to define what happens when the player succeeds, fails, or runs out of allowed time.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Using Count Up Timer with Cone Penalties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Count Up Timer can be used with <Bold>Cone Penalties</Bold>. In that setup, the visible timer
        counts upward, and hitting traffic cones can add penalty time.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Cone Penalties only makes sense if a Count Up Timer also exists. Without a Count Up Timer,
        there is no visible upward timer for Cone Penalties to modify.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_count_up_timer_cone_penalties_setup.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Cone Penalty Setup Requirements
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        For a cone penalty challenge, the following Event Points are normally required:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Count Up Timer</Bold> — starts the visible count-up timer.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cone Penalties</Bold> — adds penalty time when cone transgressions happen.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Create Barrel</Bold> Event Points set to <Bold>Traffic Cone</Bold> — the cone objects that can be hit.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The practical chain is:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Count Up Timer is active -> Traffic Cone is hit -> Cone Penalties adds penalty time
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        The Count Up Timer is the visible timer. Cone Penalties modifies that timer. The Traffic Cone
        objects provide the transgression events.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Cone setup warning:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Do not add Cone Penalties by itself and expect a visible timer.
                    The Count Up Timer must exist, and the cone objects must be created separately using Create Barrel set to Traffic Cone.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Examples
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Timed Area Challenge</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The player enters a radius and the Count Up Timer starts. The player must reach a target,
        complete an objective, or escape before other mission logic decides that too much time has
        passed.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Driving or Cone Challenge</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The timer starts when the challenge begins. Traffic cones are placed using Create Barrel.
        Cone Penalties is present so that hitting cones increases the timer.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Mission Objective Time Trial</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use Count Up Timer to show how long the player has taken to complete an optional or required
        task. Other mission Event Points can award success or failure based on the mission setup.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Visible Pressure Timer</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Start the timer when a dangerous sequence begins so the player can see time accumulating,
        even if the mission does not strictly fail at a specific threshold.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Count Up Timer Workflow
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Decide what should start the timer.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Count Up Timer</Bold> and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a letter group and colour that fits your mission organisation.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the Event Point near the area or logic it belongs to, if useful for readability.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger that starts the timer, such as Player Enters Radius, Dependency, Player Uses in Radius, or None / Game Starts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the Listening Mode according to the behaviour you need for the mission sequence.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using cone penalties, add Cone Penalties and create Traffic Cone objects using Create Barrel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add any additional success/failure logic needed for the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the mission in game.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Cone Challenge Workflow
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create the route or challenge area.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Count Up Timer</Bold> and trigger it when the challenge starts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Cone Penalties</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add <Bold>Create Barrel</Bold> Event Points and set them to <Bold>Traffic Cone</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the cones around the route.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add success/failure logic for completing or failing the challenge.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test that the timer starts, cones can be hit, and penalties increase the timer.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Troubleshooting
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The timer does not start</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Count Up Timer Event Point exists.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm its trigger condition is firing.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using Dependency, confirm the Dependency EP points to the Event Point that should start the timer.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test with None / Game Starts to confirm the timer itself works.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Cone penalties do not add time</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm a Count Up Timer exists and is active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Cone Penalties Event Point exists.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the cones were created using Create Barrel set to Traffic Cone.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the player is actually hitting the cone objects during the active challenge.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">The timer starts too early or too late</Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="32,0,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Check the trigger used by the Count Up Timer.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use a Dependency trigger if another Event Point should start the timer.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use Player Enters Radius or Player Uses in Radius if the timer should start from player action.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final note:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Count Up Timer is simple, but it often sits inside larger mission logic.
                    It starts the visible timer; the surrounding Event Points decide what the timer means.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>